Smoothing of particle size data

Jacob Cram

23 November 2020

Simple Binned ESS ESS %>% filter(depth <= 500, profile == stn_043) %>% select(depth, lb, ub, vol, TotalParticles) %>% dput

I have a data-set where particles of different sizes, at different depths in the ocean.

They are measured by an underwater vision profiler. This is a camera, that counts and sizes particles in a given volume of water.

There are frequently zero particles sampled and Id like to use what I do know about relationships between particles across size and depth to estemate the abundances of particles of different sizes at different depth.

Here are a few things that I think are mostly true. 1) Particles follow power law size distribution spectrum. That is, when you normalize particle numbers to the width of the particle size bin (see below). They have a more or less linear relatinship such that log(number) ~ log(size).

  1. Particles of any given size follow a power law size distribution with respect to depth, such that log(number) ~ log(depth).

I dont expect these relationships to be perfect, so Ive been using gams to allow for some deviation from these patterns.

Since my particles are of known number, Im assuming that they are sampled from a binomial distribution. I also tried a poisson distribution but got some strange results.

Id like to try using baysean approaches to see if I get similar results to these frequentist approaches.

Particles are binned by size. And the number of particles in each size bin, at each depth are recorded.

Here depth is measured as meters depth in the water column. lb is the lower bound of the size bin ub is the upper bound of the size bin, measured in mm, vol is the volume sampled (L) and TotalParticles are the number of particles seen in that bin.

head(data)

I make a few extra parameters. binsize is the difference between lb and ub. nparticles are the particles normalized to volume, measured in (Particles/L) and n_nparticles is the number of particles normalized both to volume and bin-size (Particles/L/mm)

data01 <- data %>% mutate(binsize = ub-lb, nparticles = TotalParticles/vol, n_nparticles = nparticles/binsize)
data01 %>% head

Here you can see generally how these profiles look. There are lots of small particles, and fewer large particles. The largist particles are not detected below the shallowist depth. The intermediatly large particles (lb 1 mm) are sometimes detected a few times, sometimes once, and sometimes not at all, below the surface.

I can also show particle abundance, normalized to binsize and volume.

nnPlot <- data01 %>% group_by(lb) %>% ggplot(aes(x = n_nparticles, y = depth, col = log(lb), group = lb)) + scale_y_reverse() + geom_point() + scale_x_log10() + scale_color_viridis_c() + geom_path() + geom_vline(xintercept = 1) + geom_vline(xintercept = 5) + labs(x = "Normalized Particles (#/L/mm)")
nnPlot

You can see that this looks similar to the plot above.

I would like to estemate the true abundance of all of these size fractions, but especially the particles of intermediate abundance, that show up sometimes once, sometimes a few times, and sometimes not at all.

I would like to estemate these from both the abundance of particles above and below that particle, but also from the abundance of smaller particles.

The data at each depth, sort-of follow a power law, where the log of the size is more-or-less linearly related to the log of the volume and bin-width normalized abundance.

data_125m <- data01 %>% filter(depth == 125)
data_125m %>% ggplot(aes(x = lb, y = n_nparticles)) + scale_x_log10() + scale_y_log10() + geom_point()

Of course, the large particles are so rare that we dont detect them, so the line flattens off eventually.

I can fit this with a glm with a negative binomial family, if I assume that the particles are distributed at random.

myGlm <- function(df){
  MASS::glm.nb(TotalParticles ~ log(lb) + offset(log(vol * binsize)), data = df)
}

mod_125m <- myGlm(data_125m)
summary(mod_125m)

So here, the open circles are the predicted values. For my subsequent analyses, I could for instance use these to estemate the larger particles, when we dont see them, or all large particles.

Another option, is to use a gam. In this case, everything is pretty linear, but gams allow for some deviation from the power law relationship.

myGam <- function(df){
  gam(TotalParticles ~ s(log(lb)), offset = log(vol * binsize), family = nb(), data = df)
}

mod1_125m <- myGam(data_125m)
summary(mod1_125m)

This gets me a slightly bendier line, with wider (and I think more believable) confedence intervals. Every observed, non-zero, value is inside of the confedence intervals Also, for the points with no values, the confedence intervals get larger.

Here are some bookkeeping functions, that allow us to redo the above calculations with one function.

expand_with_gam <- function(df, mod){
  loc_pred <- predict(mod, type = "link", se.fit = TRUE) %>% as.data.frame %>% mutate(lower = fit - 2 * se.fit, upper = fit + 2 * se.fit) %>% mutate(resp_fit = exp(fit), resp_lower = exp(lower), resp_upper = exp(upper))
  loc_df <- bind_cols(df, loc_pred)
  loc_df
}

gam_size_ggplot <- function(df){
  ggplot(df, aes(x = lb)) + geom_point(aes(y = resp_fit), shape = 1) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = resp_lower, ymax = resp_upper)) + 
  geom_point(aes(y = n_nparticles)) + scale_x_log10() + scale_y_log10()
}

Test

expand_with_gam(df_125m, mod1_125m) %>% gam_size_ggplot

verticalGam <- function(df){
  gam(TotalParticles ~ s(log(depth)), offset = log(vol * binsize), family = nb(), data = df)
}
